"Osteomyelitis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_id_s26_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"5b1912",
"children":[
"Microorganisms infect bone by:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"e0716f",
"children":[
"contiguous spread from adjacent soft tissue or joints; usually polymicrobial"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f01a05",
"children":[
"hematogenous seeding; most commonly identified is ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Staphylococcus aureus"
]
}
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"7a3ae5",
"children":[
"direct inoculation as a result of surgery or trauma; usually polymicrobial"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1e2fd6",
"children":[
"Pain at the involved site without systemic symptoms is the typical presentation. Consider osteomyelitis when chronic wounds do not respond to appropriate therapy. ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Patients who have undergone total joint arthroplasty and have new or unresolved joint pain may have a prosthetic joint infection."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_id_s26_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_id_s26_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"84954e",
"children":[
"Select radiography as the first imaging test; it can confirm the diagnosis if typical findings are present but cannot exclude the diagnosis if negative. If plain radiography is not diagnostic, select MRI; if contraindicated, select CT. Half of patients with acute hematogenous osteomyelitis will have positive blood cultures."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"afe5b3",
"children":[
"Bone biopsy is the definitive diagnostic study for osteomyelitis. A positive blood culture obviates the need for a bone biopsy. ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"In stable chronic osteomyelitis (absent cellulitis or bacteremia), withhold antimicrobial therapy until deep bone cultures have been obtained."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0066b5",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"S. aureus"
]
},
" (including ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus",
"children":[
"MRSA"
]
},
") is the most common cause of vertebral osteomyelitis. MRI is the most sensitive imaging modality to detect vertebral osteomyelitis. Patients with imaging studies suggestive of vertebral osteomyelitis but negative blood cultures should undergo a CT-guided percutaneous needle biopsy."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"6000e8",
"children":[
"Do not obtain sinus tract and wound drainage cultures."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_id_s26_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ec0e03",
"children":[
"For all patients:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"b64d86",
"children":[
"administration of culture-guided antimicrobials (usually 4-6 weeks)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a1dc29",
"children":[
"surgical debridement (if warranted)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"65bfd3",
"children":[
"removal of orthopedic prosthetic devices (if feasible)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f92b43",
"children":[
"Patients with ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"vertebral osteomyelitis"
]
},
" and neurologic compromise or spinal instability should undergo evaluation for immediate surgical intervention. Patients with sepsis, neurologic deficit, spinal instability, or epidural abscess should receive empiric antibiotic therapy. Vancomycin or daptomycin plus ceftriaxone, ceftazidime, cefepime, or a fluoroquinolone are appropriate choices."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d7b344",
"children":[
"For ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"diabetic foot infections with osteomyelitis"
]
},
", bone biopsy and culture directs antibiotic selection."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"3958ed",
"children":[
"In patients with poor arterial vascular supply, also choose revascularization."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"7f4378",
"children":[
"Surgery is not needed for uncomplicated hematogenous vertebral osteomyelitis."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0599fe",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"A positive MRI persists long after effective therapy for osteomyelitis; do not obtain follow-up MRI in patients improving clinically."
]
},
" "
]
},
" "
]
},
{
